<h1>Star formation in the circumgalactic high-velocity cloud Complex H (He et al., arXiv:2603.10607)</h1>

<section>
  <h2>Paper metadata</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Title:</strong> Star formation in the circumgalactic high-velocity cloud Complex H</li>
    <li><strong>Authors:</strong> He et al.</li>
    <li><strong>arXiv:</strong> 2603.10607 — <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.10607">https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.10607</a></li>
    <li><strong>Date:</strong> 2026-03-16 (arXiv submission)</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Summary / Key findings</h2>
  <p>
    He et al. report the discovery of a binary young stellar cluster (named Emei-1 and Emei-2) embedded in the Southern part of High-Velocity Cloud Complex H (SCH). The clusters are very young (age = 11.2 ± 0.6 Myr) and lie at a distance of 13.8 ± 0.6 kpc, providing a direct stellar distance anchor for Complex H. Spectroscopy of the brightest members yields sub-solar metallicities (Z ≈ 0.04–0.06 Z_sun). The systemic cloud velocity is v_lsr ≈ -180 km/s with measured stellar radial velocities for two bright members of -202 ± 5 km/s and -158 ± 1 km/s, tying the stars to the HVC gas. Cold HI cores with low velocity dispersion (σ_v ~ 2 km/s) and compact sizes are identified in EBHIS 21 cm maps at matching velocities.
  </p>

  <p>
    Implications: this is a direct confirmation that star formation can occur inside HVCs / the circumgalactic medium (CGM). The authors argue internal cloud-cloud collisions within Complex H likely triggered the star formation. Orbit and drag modelling indicate Complex H is on a prograde, south-to-north orbit and interacting with the outer Galactic disk; outer layers are decelerating and mixing with disk gas. The rapid dynamical decoupling of young stars from their natal gas (&lt;~20 Myr) helps explain the observational rarity of stars found in HVCs.
  </p>
</section>

