<section>
  <h2>Key numbers & claims</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Cluster ages: 11.2 ± 0.6 Myr (Emei-1/Emei-2)</li>
    <li>Distance: 13.8 ± 0.6 kpc (direct stellar distance to Complex H)</li>
    <li>Stellar metallicity: Z ≈ 0.04^{+0.06}_{-0.02} and 0.06^{+0.07}_{-0.03} Z_sun (sub-solar)</li>
    <li>Systemic cloud velocity: &lt;v_lsr&gt; ≈ -180 km/s</li>
    <li>Measured stellar v_lsr (two members): -202 ± 5 km/s and -158 ± 1 km/s</li>
    <li>HI cold core peak v_lsr = -181 km/s; cold gas velocity dispersion σ_v ≈ 2 km/s; warm gas σ_v ≈ 15 km/s</li>
    <li>Cold core physical size (channel 2): ≈ 320 × 99 pc (beam-deconvolved)</li>
    <li>Ambient disk gas density upper limit from drag modelling: ρ_ambient ≲ 1e-24 g cm^-3</li>
    <li>Complex H shows a "slow–fast–slow" (SFS) latitude–velocity pattern spanning ≈ 100 km/s across ≈ 15°
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Data & methods</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Gaia astrometry for member selection, parallaxes, and proper motions</li>
    <li>LAMOST spectroscopy for spectral types, radial velocities, and metallicity estimates of the brightest members</li>
    <li>EBHIS 21 cm HI survey channel maps and peak-velocity maps for cold-core identification and kinematics</li>
    <li>Orbit integration with simple drag modelling to constrain trajectory and ambient density</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Implications / Discussion</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Direct evidence that star formation can occur in the CGM inside HVCs; HVCs can host young stellar systems.</li>
    <li>HVC-cloud interactions (cloud-cloud collisions) may be an efficient trigger for star formation in low-metallicity circumgalactic gas.</li>
    <li>Young HVC-born stars rapidly decouple from gas, making them hard to associate with HVCs after ≳20 Myr.</li>
    <li>Non-detections of CO in HVCs do not rule out star formation—low metallicity and dispersed molecular gas reduce CO brightness; cold HI cores are promising molecular/star-formation targets.</li>
    <li>Potential contribution of HVC-born stars to halo stellar populations and some hypervelocity-star-like phenomena.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Open questions</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>How common is star formation in HVCs? Detection bias favors extremely young systems.</li>
    <li>What is the long-term fate of clusters formed in HVCs—tidal disruption vs survival and contribution to halo populations?</li>
    <li>Are there observable chemical abundance patterns in HVC-born stars that can identify them in the halo?</li>
    <li>Can deeper targeted molecular observations (CO, dust, other tracers) reveal the molecular phase in cold HI cores?</li>
  </ul>
</section>

